text: Appl Microbiol Biotechnol (2013) 97:2413–2421 DOI 10.1007/s00253-012-4505-2 Strict control of auricin production in Streptomyces aureofaciens CCM 3239 involves a feedback mechanism Peter Kutas & Lubomira Feckova & Alena Rehakova & Renata Novakova & Dagmar Homerova & Erik Mingyar & Bronislava Rezuchova & Beatrica Sevcikova & Jan Kormanec Received: 29 August 2012 / Revised: 26 September 2012 / Accepted: 6 October 2012 / Published online: 19 October 2012 # Springer-Verlag Berlin Heidelberg 2012 Abstract The polyketide gene cluster aur1 is responsible for the production of the angucycline antibiotic auricin in Streptomyces aureofaciens CCM 3239. Auricin pro- duction is regulated in a complex manner involving several regulators, including a key pathway-specific pos- itive regulator Aur1P that belongs to the family of ‘atypical’ response regulators. Production of auricin is induced after entry into stationary phase. However, auri- cin was produced in only a short time interval of several hours. We found that the decrease of auricin production was due to a strict regulation of auricin biosynthetic genes at the transcriptional level by a feed- back mechanism; auricin and/or its intermediate(s) inhibited binding of Aur1P to its cognate biosynthetic promoter aur1Ap and consequently stopped its activation. In addition, we also determined that synthesised auricin is unsta- ble during growth of S. aureofaciens CCM3239 in the produc- tion medium even though purified auricin is stable for days in various organic solvents. The critical parameter affecting its stability was pH. Auricin is stable at acid pH and unstable at neutral and alkaline pH. The drop in auricin concentration was due to an increase of pH shortly after induction of auricin production during cultivation of S. aureofaciens CCM3239.

Keywords Antibiotics . Auricin . Polyketide . Regulation . Secondary metabolite . Streptomyces P. Kutas : L. Feckova : A. Rehakova : R. Novakova : D. Homerova : E. Mingyar : B. Rezuchova : B. Sevcikova : J. Kormanec (*) Institute of Molecular Biology, Slovak Academy of Sciences, Dubravska cesta 21, 845 51, Bratislava, Slovak Republic e-mail: jan.kormanec@savba.sk BIOTECHNOLOGICAL PRODUCTS AND PROCESS ENGINEERING Streptomycetes are Gram-positive soil bacteria that undergo an exceptional process of morphological differentiation, accompanied by so-called ‘physiological differentiation’, characterised by extensive production of biologically active secondary metabolites, including many antibiotics with important applications in human medicine and agricul- ture. The genes required for antibiotic biosynthesis are generally clustered and co-regulated by pathway-specific transcriptional activators that are located in these clusters. Expression of these regulatory genes is controlled by complex regulatory mechanisms that determine the onset of antibiotic production (Bibb 2005; Martin and Liras 2010).

We have previously identified a type II polyketide syn- thase (PKS) gene cluster, aur1, which is responsible for production of the angucycline-like polyketide antibiotic auricin in Streptomyces aureofaciens CCM 3239 (Novakova et al. 2002). Although auricin has been readily detected, its purification and structural elucidation has been hampered by very low yields. A similar phenotype has been described for several homologous angucycline clusters in other strepto- mycetes like alp (Pang et al. 2004), pga (Metsa-Ketela et al. 2004), and ovm (Lombo et al. 2004), indicating that these PKS clusters might be strictly regulated or induced by specific conditions. Structural studies of auricin are still under investigation, but preliminary results revealed its mole- cular weight as 541.2 and confirmed its angucycline polyke- tide ring conjugated with amino deoxyhexose D-forosamine, indicating that it is a unique antibiotic of the angucycline family (J. Kormanec, unpublished results). Sequence analysis of the auricin gene cluster revealed several putative regulatory genes that indicate a complex regulation of auricin production. Several of the genes have already been characterised. The aur1P gene, encoding a

protein which belongs to the family of ‘atypical’ response regulators (Wang et al. 2009), has been shown to specifical- ly activate expression of the auricin biosynthetic genes by a direct binding and activation of the aur1Ap promoter directing expression of 22 structural genes (aur1A-aur1U) of the auricin cluster (Novakova et al. 2005, 2011a). The aur1R gene, encoding a protein homologous to transcriptional repressors of the TetR family, belongs to the subfamily of γ-butyrolactone autoregulator pseudo-receptors, which constitute an indepen- dent branch in the phylogenetic tree of γ-butyrolactone autor- egulator receptors that likely do not bind γ-butyrolactone autoregulators (Nishida et al. 2007). It has been shown to repress expression of the aur1P gene. Aur1R directly binds the aur1Pp promoter and this binding was abolished by the presence of auricin and/or its intermediates (Novakova et al. 2010). The other regulatory gene, aur1PR3, encoding a homologue of the SARP family of transcriptional activators (Wietzorreck and Bibb 1997), has been found to be involved in auricin regulation, and it is also under the direct control of Aur1R (Novakova et al. 2011b). The aim of the present study was to investigate why auricin production occurs in a narrow time interval during growth of S. aureofaciens CCM3239 and the reason for high instability of auricin during cultivation. We show that a feedback transcriptional regulation and pH fluctuation are responsible for these phenotypes. Bacterial strains and culture conditions

S. aureofaciens CCM 3239 wild-type was from the Czecho- slovak Collection of Microorganisms, Brno, Czech Republic. Growth of S. aureofaciens CCM 3239 strains was carried out in liquid minimal NMP medium (Kieser et al. 2000) and rich Bennet medium (Horinouchi et al. 1983) as described in Novakova et al. (2010). For RNA isolation from liquid- grown cultures, 5×108 c.f.u. of S. aureofaciens CCM3239 spores were inoculated in 50 ml Bennet medium in 250 ml Erlenmayer flasks and grown on orbital shaker at 270 rpm and 28 °C to different growth phases. RNA isolation and S1 nuclease mapping Isolation of total RNA from S. aureofaciens CCM 3239 and high-resolution S1 nuclease mapping were performed according to Kormanec (2001). Samples (40 μg) of RNA were hybridised to approximately 0.015 pmol of suitable DNA probe labelled at one 5′ end with [γ-32P] ATP (approximately 106 dpmpmol−1 of probe). The S1 probe for the aur1Ap promoter has been described previously (Novakova et al. 2005), and the control hrdBp2 promoter probe has been described in Kormanec and Farkasovsky (1993). The primers were labelled at the 5′ end with [γ-32P] ATP (ICN, 4500 Cimmol−1) and T4 polynucleotide kinase as described in Ausubel et al. (1995). The protected DNA fragments were analysed on DNA sequencing gels together with G+A and T+C sequencing ladders derived from the end- labelled fragments (Maxam and Gilbert 1980). Electrophoretic mobility-shift assay

A 200-bp SmaI-EcoRI DNA fragment encompassing the aur1Ap promoter uniquely labelled on the 5′ end at the EcoRI site and His-tagged Aur1P protein were prepared as described in Novakova et al. (2005). Electrophoretic mobility-shift assay (EMSA) was done essentially as described by Ausubel et al. (1995). The 32P-labelled DNA fragment (0.01 ng, approx. 2 000 dpm) was incubated with 5 μg of purified Aur1P protein for 15 min at 30 °C in 15 μl total volume of the binding buffer (12.5 mM Tris at pH 7.9, 60 mM KCl, 1 mM EDTA, 1 mM DTT and 12 % (v/v) glycerol), 2 μg sonicated salmon sperm DNA and 4.5 μg BSA. After incubation, protein-bound and free DNA were resolved on a nondenaturing polyacrylamide gel containing 4 % (w/v) acrylamide, 0.05 % (w/v) bisacrylamide, and 2.5 % (w/v) glycerol, running at 4 °C (after 1 h prerun at 30 mA) in a high-ionic-strength buffer containing 50 mM Tris, 380 mM glycine, 2 mM EDTA, pH 8.5 at the same current. The gels were dried and exposed to an X-ray film. The effect of auricin on the ability of Aur1P to bind the DNA probe was tested by adding 1 μl of the undiluted extracts or a series of twofold diluted extracts (with methanol) to the 15 μl EMSA binding reaction. Analysis of S. aureofaciens CCM3239 growth and auricin production

Spores (5×108 c.f.u) of S. aureofaciens CCM 3239 wild- type strain were inoculated into 50 ml Bennet medium in 250 ml Erlenmayer flasks and the cultures grown on orbital shaker at 270 r.p.m. and 28 °C. Five-millilitre aliquots were taken from the cultures at particular time points and filtrated through GF/C glass microfibre filters (Whatman). The filters were air-dried for 3 h and weighed for dry mass for growth curve data. The pH of culture supernatants was measured after filtration, and 4-ml aliquots were extracted twice with the same volume of ethylacetate. Residual water was re- moved with sodium sulphate and sodium chloride, and extracts were evaporated under vacuum. The pellets were dissolved in 100 μl of methanol, and 1- and 10-μl aliquots were subjected to thin-layer chromatography (TLC) analysis on silica gel 60 F254 plates (Merck) with n-butanol saturated with water. Dried TLC plates with 1-μl aliquots were ana- lysed by biochromatography placing them on LB agar plates Appl Microbiol Biotechnol (2013) 97:2413–2421 Appl Microbiol Biotechnol (2013) 97:2413–2421

and overlaying with soft nutrient agar (Kieser et al. 2000), containing a fresh culture of Bacillus subtilis. The agar was allowed to solidify and plates were incubated for 16 h at 37 °C and screened visually for growth-inhibition zones. Twenty- microlitre aliquots of the extract were analyses by reverse phase HPLC in an OmmiSpher 5 C18 column (5 μm, 250× 4.6 mm, Varian, Lake Forest, CA) on a Varian ProStar HPLC system with a ProStar 325 UV–vis detector (Varian, Lake Forest, CA) with acetonitrile and 0.5 % (v/v) acetic acid in water as a mobile phase and dual detection at 254 and 450 nm. Elution was carried out with a linear gradient of acetonitril from 20 to 100 % for 30 min at a flow rate 1 ml/min. Under these conditions, auricin exhibited a retention time of 9.3 min. The concentration of auricin in culture filtrates was quantified by comparing chromatographic peak areas at 254 nm (a mean of three independent experiments) with those obtained using standards of known concentrations prepared from purified auricin. Auricin production was confirmed by HRESI-MS analysis as a molecular ion [M+H] of m/z0542.2039 with detection in the positive mode. HRESI-MS was measured with a Q-Tof Premier mass spectrometer (Waters).

For stability tests auricin was purified as above but in a larger scale from 600 ml of growth culture after 16 h of cultivation. Evaporated ethylacetate extract was dissolved in 2 ml of chloroform/methanol (95:5), loaded to 5 ml silica flesh column (0.04–0.063 mm, Silicagel 60, Merck) and eluted with 20 ml chloroform/methanol (95:5). The sample was vacuum evaporated, dissolved in 250 μl of methanol, filtrated and purified by semipreprarative reverse-phase HPLC on Dynamax 5 C18 column (5 μm, 250×10 mm; Varian, Lake Forest, CA) using the same conditions as above except that the flow rate was 4 ml/min. Purified auricin was analysed by TLC biochromatography and HPLC in stability tests as described above. Extracts used for EMSA were prepared from S. aureofa- ciens CCM 3239 and the S. aureofaciens, aur1::tsr (Novakova et al. 2002) grown in 50 ml media as described above, but the whole culture media together with mycelium were extracted twice with ethylacetate and finally dissolved in 30 μl of methanol. Time course of auricin production Auricin production in the wild-type S. aureofaciens CCM3239 strain was investigated in detail during cultiva- tion in liquid Bennet medium that is optimal for auricin production. Ethyl acetate extracts from the strain grown to different time points were analysed by TLC followed by a bioassay

against B. subtilis as described previously (Novakova et al. 2011b). As shown by TLC alone (Fig. 1c), auricin (Rf value00.13) is a yellow compound with an absorption inhibits growth of Gram- maximum at 438 nm that positive B. subtilis strain (Fig. 1d). Interestingly, the time course of auricin production in S. aureofaciens CCM3239 revealed that the antibiotic is produced only in a rather narrow time interval. As for many other antibiotics, production of auricin begins at the beginning the stationary phase (12 h) and no auricin was of detected during exponential phase (10 h). Then its level increased with the maximum at 16 h. However, then its amount rapidly decreased, and at 26 h we could not time course was also detect any auricin. A similar observed in minimal NMP medium (data not shown). Auricin production was investigated in parallel by HPLC of ethylacetate extracts, and the results (Fig. 1b) corroborated the TLC data. Intriguingly, we could not detect any dominant degradation products even when scanning across the UV range, only many small peaks of faster mobility continuously appeared and finally also disappeared. Expression of auricin biosynthetic genes during growth

This decrease of auricin production might indicate a strict regulation at the transcriptional level for this specific growth phase period. We previously characterised the aur1Ap pro- moter governing expression of the first characterised bio- synthetic gene of the auricin cluster, aur1A, (Novakova et al. 2002). This promoter directs transcription of a long mRNA of about 20,000 nucleotides covering almost the whole aur1 cluster (Novakova et al. 2011a). To investigate the expression of auricin biosynthetic genes during this critical period of stationary phase with decreased auricin production, S1 nuclease mapping was performed using RNA isolated from S. aureofaciens CCM3239 wild-type strain cultivated in liquid Bennet medium at these time points. As shown in Fig. 2, a single RNA-protected frag- ment was identified with TSPs that corresponded to the aur1Ap promoter as published previously (Novakova et al. 2002, 2011b). The promoter was inactive in exponential growth phase (10 h) and induced at the beginning of the stationary phase (12 h) thus correlating with auricin produc- tion. However, the levels of the aur1Ap mRNA decreased in the late stationary phase in the time points that precede the dramatic decrease of auricin production. As an internal control, S1 nuclease mapping was performed with the same RNA samples using a probe fragment specific for the S. aureofaciens hrdBp2 promoter, which is expressed fairly constantly during growth and differentiation (Kormanec and Farkasovsky 1993). The results indicated some tran- scriptional negative control mechanism of the aur1 cluster in late stationary phase. Each point represents the mean of three assays. b HPLC analysis of auricin production in the ethylacetate extracts from S. aureofaciens CCM 3239 strain grown in Bennet medium to the time points indicated. Auricin is marked by the arrow.

Binding of the Aur1P activator protein to the aur1Ap promoter is affected by auricin or its intermediate(s) The auricin-specific positive regulator Aur1P activates auri- cin biosynthetic genes by a direct binding and activation of the aur1Ap promoter (Novakova et al. 2005). To investigate the possibility that auricin or its intermediate is an effector ligand for Aur1P that might negatively affect its binding to the promoter, an EMSA analysis was done as described previously for effector binding to Aur1R protein (Novakova et al. 2010). The whole culture media with mycelium of S. aureofaciens CCM 3239 and its isogenic S. aureofaciens, aur1::tsr mutant with a deletion of critical PKS genes, which did not produce auricin (Novakova et al. 2002), grown for 14 h in Bennet medium were extracted by ethyl- acetate, dried and dissolved in methanol. An increasing concentration of extract from the wild-type S. aureofaciens dissociated Aur1P from the promoter regions, but similar amounts of extract from the aur1-disrupted S. aureofaciens strain had no effect on Aur1P binding (Fig. 3). Thus, auricin or its intermediate(s) likely represent ligand(s) that after binding to pathway- specific activator Aur1P relieve its binding to the aur1Ap promoter and consequently stop activation of the promoter. already synthesised auricin quickly disappeared in the later stages of the growth, indicating that the antibiotic is also rather unstable during later stages of growth in the produc- tion Bennet medium. To rule out some enzymatic degrada- tion by cells, the stability of the HPLC-purified auricin was analysed in fresh sterile Bennet medium at pH 7.2 by TLC biochromatography. Actually after 1 h there was dramatic decrease of activity and auricin disappeared after 4 h (Fig. 4). Auricin was similarly unstable also after cultivation in other cultivation media (data not shown). However, auri- cin was stable in water and even more stable for at least 6 days at 28 °C without a significant decrease of activity in various organic solvents (Fig. 4). We therefore tested all the parameters that might affect auricin stability and found out that the critical parameter affecting its stability was pH. Auricin was much more stable in Bennet medium with acid pH (Fig. 4). Moreover, we tested stability of purified auricin by TLC biochromatography in several overlapping 25 mM buffers of different pH. Clearly, increasing pH has a dramatic negative effect on auricin stability. While auricin was stable for at least 6 days at pH 5 (with only a partial decrease of activity), at pH 6 it disappeared after 48 h, in pH 7 after 24 h, at pH 8 after 4 h and at pH 9 auricin disappeared almost imme- diately during spotting of the TLC plate (Fig. 4). The results were also verified by HPLC analysis (Fig. 5). The stability of purified auricin in acetonitrile was rather good and after 6 days incubation at 28 °C there was only about 20 % decrease of the peak of auricin. A similar stability of auricin was observed after incubation in 0.1 % acetic acid titrated to pH 5 with ammonium, where after 6 days incubation there was also only about 20 % decrease of the auricin peak. As mentioned above, many small peaks of faster mobility that continuously appeared and disappeared could represent various auricin degradation products. The slower decomposi- tion of purified auricin during incubation at pH 7 (Fig. 5) compared to fast degradation during fermentation (Fig. 1) is due to an aeration of the fermentation medium. Oxygen is likely another factor affecting stability of auricin. Actually, we found that stability of auricin is affected by the extent of aeration, and auricin was stable for longer after decreasing aeration (growth on orbital shaker at 160 rpm). However, this lower aeration resulted also in decrease of auricin yield (data not shown).

To see whether pH varies during cultivation of S. aureo- faciens CCM3239, we measured pH during growth and in parallel estimated auricin production and growth. Actually, as seen in Fig. 1a, the pH dropped from the starting neutral pH at 0 h to pH 5 at 14 h that corresponded to the entry into stationary phase and also with the peak of auricin produc- tion. However, subsequently the pH gradually increased up to a value of pH 7.8 at 30 h. This increase of pH correlated with the time points of decreased auricin activity. The varia- tion of pH was not due to the auricin production, as a similar pH time course was found in the auricin non-producing mutant (data not shown). Therefore the production of auricin is regulated by a feedback mechanism at the transcrip- tional level and its activity is also lowered by an increase of pH in the medium after its production. Auricin is rather stable at low pH and is quickly degraded in neutral and alkaline pH. Streptomycetes and other actinobacteria represent a rich source of natural secondary products of clinical, agricultural and biotechnological value. Traditionally, production of most known antibiotics is triggered during growth of Strep- tomyces producing strain in optimal production medium after entry into stationary phase, and the respective antibi- otic is gradually accumulated after several days of further cultivation. Genome sequencing of several Streptomyces strains has revealed that they possess a much larger coding capacity for secondary metabolites than expected from their know production capacity (Bentley et al. 2002; Ikeda et al. 2003; Gross 2007). Thus, it is likely that many of the antibiotic clusters are strictly regulated and expressed only at specific conditions. Therefore the comprehensive investi- gation of antibiotic regulation may reveal mechanisms for activation of these silent secondary metabolite clusters. Results of our current study represent a contribution to this approach. Previously, we found that auricin is produced in very low amount after standard longer cultivation (Novakova et al. 2002, 2005). However, the present data revealed that auricin was produced in a very narrow time interval of several

Forty microgrammes of the purified auricin was dissolved in 0.2 ml acetonitril or 0.1 % acetic acid titrated to the indicated pH with ammonium. At the time point indicated 20 μl of hours after entry into stationary phase, then it dramatically decreased, and only traces of auricin could be detected in older cultures. This unusual phenomenon is likely related to a strict complex regulation of auricin biosynthesis involving multiple transcriptional regulators and environmental factors. Actually, the present results indicated that a transcriptional feedback mechanism is in part responsible for this decrease. Decreased transcription of aur1Ap biosynthetic promoter in later stages of growth (18 and 20 h) confirmed that the decrease in the biosynthesis of auricin is associated with strict regulation at the transcriptional level. Since binding of the auricin pathway- specific transcriptional activator Aur1P activates biosynthetic promoter aur1Ap (Novakova et al. 2005), we investigated the possible influence of effector ligands to this binding. We established that the DNA-binding activity of Aur1P is abol- ished in the presence of extracts prepared from S. aureofaciens CCM3239 grown in production medium for 14 h, coincident with the presence of auricin, while similar extracts from the auricin non-producing strain were ineffective. Thus, it seems that auricin and/or its intermediate(s) bind to Aur1P resulting in dissociation of the protein from aur1Ap and consequently repression of its transcription. Therefore, a specific high level of auricin and/or its intermediate is responsible for feedback transcriptional control of this promoter. regulation by binding of the end product was described for other homologous ‘atypical’ response regulators in two angu- cycline gene clusters: JadR1 of the Streptomyces venezuelae jadomycin cluster and SimReg1 of the Streptomyces antibio- ticus Tu6040 simocyclinone cluster. JadR1 DNA-binding activity was inhibited with the final product of jadomycin B biosynthetic genes (Wang et al. 2009), and likewise extracts enriched with simocyclinone and/or its intermediates were responsible for abolishment of SimReg1 DNA-binding activity (Horbal et al. 2012). Therefore, it seems that this feedback mechanism is widespread for these ‘atypical’ response regulators involved in antibiotic regulation. The proposed physiological reason of this intriguing feedback mechanism is to modulate precisely the level of these anti- biotics (Wang et al. 2009). However, although this decrease of auricin production was due to a strict regulation of auricin biosynthetic genes at the transcriptional level by a feedback mechanism, it was intriguing that already synthesised auricin quickly disap- peared from the growth medium during growth of S. aur- eofaciens CCM3239, although purified auricin was stable for several days in various organic solvents. Our results revealed that the critical parameter affecting auricin stability was pH. Auricin was found to be stable at acid pH but

unstable at neutral and alkaline pH. The pH values of cultivation medium fluctuated during growth of S. aureofa- ciens CCM3239 from neutral pH 7.2 at the time of inocu- lation to acid pH 5 at the time point corresponding to the beginning of stationary phase. This time point (14 h) coin- cides with the highest level of auricin. Afterwards the pH gradually increased towards alkaline values, which was accompanied by quick degradation of auricin (Fig. 1a). This acidification of growth media due to an export of organic acids has been observed for many Streptomyces spp. These organic acids are then gradually reutilised that results in neutralisation of cultivation medium (Dekleva et al. 1985; Madden et al. 1996; Surowitz 1985; Susstrunk et al. 1998). To increase auricin production we performed a series of fermentations with acid-buffered media. When S. aureofa- ciens CCM3239 was grown in buffered media to pH 5 and 6, it grew poorly and produced low levels of auricin. How- ever, when optimal cultivation Bennet medium (pH 7.2) was buffered at the time point 14 h (with the highest level of auricin) to pH 5 (adjusting to 25 mM MES-NaOH, pH 5), this level of auricin was stable for several days, but there was no additional increase, likely due to a feedback regula- tory effect (data not shown).

Based on the known data including the present results we can suggest a following model for auricin regulation. Aur1R, as a negative regulator of auricin biosynthesis, blocks transcription of the genes encoding the pathway- specific activators Aur1P and Aur1PR3, until the bacterial cells are fully prepared for auricin production, by for exam- ple permitting earlier expression of auricin resistance. How- ever, aur1R expression is induced after entry into stationary phase, and some mechanism, possibly a γ-butyrolactone system, should exist to block its transcription in exponential phase. Actually, a γ-butyrolactone receptor protein SagR has been found to inhibit expression of aur1R at early exponential phase (J. Kormanec, unpublished results). Then some low level of auricin or its intermediate(s) produced by a basal expression of auricin biosynthetic genes after the entry into stationary phase binds to Aur1R to relieve this inhibition. Consequently, this induced transcription of aur1P and aur1PR3 results in accumulation of threshold amounts of these pathway-specific activators to induce ex- pression of auricin biosynthetic genes resulting in a fast increase of auricin production. However, the resulting high level of auricin binds to Aur1P and hinders its binding to the biosynthetic promoter(s). This constitutes a feedback con- trol of auricin biosynthesis in S. aureofaciens CCM3239, and auricin is then quickly degraded by an increase of pH of the cultivation medium. Our present results might be also helpful for characterisa- tion of other similar antibiotic clusters. For instance, the aur1 cluster is most similar to the cryptic angucycline cluster pga in Streptomyces sp. PGA64 (Metsa-Ketela et al. 2004). It is rational to assume that this antibiotic might have similar features and could be regulated by a complex strict mecha- nism and produced in a short time interval.

In conclusion, we clarified mechanisms that limit auricin production to a short period during fermentation in liquid media. The decrease of auricin production was due to a strict regulation of its biosynthetic genes at the transcriptional level by a feedback mechanism, where auricin and/or its intermediate(s) bind to the pathway-specific activator Aur1P and inhibit activation of its cognate biosynthetic promoter aur1Ap. Moreover, synthesised auricin is unstable during growth of S. aureofaciens CCM3239. The critical parameter affecting its stability was pH. Auricin is stable at acid pH, but unstable at neutral and alkaline pH.
